{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WQ9c2EscC4jcis4v6GT9hN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Technical Debt & Temporary Fixes\n2\t\n3\tTrack temporary hacks, relaxed rules, and shortcuts here. \n4\t**Goal**: Eliminate these items before V1 Launch (or explicitly defer them).\n5\t\n6\t---\n7\t\n8\t## High Priority (Fix ASAP)\n9\t\n10\t(none)\n11\t\n12\t---\n13\t\n14\t## Medium Priority (Before Launch)\n15\t\n16\t### [Backend] `rateLimitGlobal` is route-local, not app-global\n17\t- **Date**: 2026-04-21\n18\t- **Location**: `backend/src/middleware/rate-limit.ts`, `backend/src/index.ts`, `backend/src/index-waitlist.ts`\n19\t- **What**: `createRateLimitMiddleware(...)` allocates fresh in-memory state per middleware instance, so `rateLimitGlobal` only applies within each mounted route group (`/auth/*`, `/flip-you/*`, `/pot-shot/*`, `/closecall/bet`, waitlist routes) instead of enforcing one shared global bucket across the app.\n20\t- **Current mitigation**: Cloudflare now provides a coarse host-level backstop in front of the API, and route-local in-app limits still protect individual endpoints.\n21\t- **Proper solution**: Either (1) implement a truly shared in-process/global limiter bucket for all route groups that are meant to share `rateLimitGlobal`, or (2) rename/configure the setting to make the route-local scope explicit and document it accordingly.\n22\t- **Why not now**: Current edge rate limiting reduces immediate flood risk, and changing limiter state sharing touches request-shaping behavior that should be validated separately.\n23\t\n24\t### [Backend] Public referral code check endpoint — remove at prod\n25\t- **Date**: 2026-04-15\n26\t- **Location**: `backend/src/routes/public-referral.ts` — `GET /public-referral/code/:code`\n27\t- **What**: Unauthenticated endpoint that checks whether a referral code exists. Added for the waitlist pre-connect flow. Leaks code-existence info without auth — acceptable for waitlist but unnecessary attack surface once the main app launches.\n28\t- **Current mitigation**: Returns only `{ exists: boolean }` (no user info). Regex-validates input.\n29\t- **Proper solution**: Remove endpoint once waitlist is retired and the main app handles referral flows behind auth.\n30\t\n31\t### ~~[Telegram] Webhook errors are too opaque and retry-prone~~\n32\t- **Resolved**: 2026-04-09 — `telegram/src/app.ts` now catches outbound reply delivery failures, logs webhook context, and still returns `200` to Telegram; `telegram/src/telegram-api.ts` now includes Telegram error bodies in thrown errors for faster diagnosis.\n33\t\n34\t### [Challenge Engine] SOL crate payout handler needs production review\n35\t- **Date**: 2026-04-03\n36\t- **Location**: `backend/src/queue/handlers/crate-sol-payout.ts`\n37\t- **What**: `CRATE_SOL_PAYOUT` handler sends SOL from server keypair to player wallet. Needs manual review before production enablement — verify transfer amounts, error handling, retry behavior, and rate limiting against real treasury wallet.\n38\t- **Current mitigation**: Handler marks failed transfers as terminal (no retry). Integration-tested with mock connection only.\n39\t- **Proper solution**: (1) Add retry logic with max attempts (like referral-claim handler), (2) Add rate limiting per user, (3) Verify payout amounts against pool balance, (4) Test with real devnet treasury wallet, (5) Add monitoring/alerting for failed payouts.\n40\t- **Why not now**: M1 launch — handler structure is correct, needs ops hardening before real SOL flows through it.\n41\t\n42\t### ~~[Pot Shot] Backend game-engine PDA helper uses stale `roundNumber` seed~~\n43\t- **Resolved**: 2026-04-02 — `getRoundPda(matchId: Buffer)` already uses correct seed. Confirmed in gap analysis for spec 101.\n44\t\n45\t---\n46\t\n47\t## Low Priority (Post-Launch cleanup)\n48\t\n49\t### [Challenge Engine] Extract to separate service\n50\t- **Date**: 2026-04-04\n51\t- **Location**: `backend/src/queue/handlers/` (game-settled, reward-pool-fund, points-grant, crate-drop, crate-sol-payout), `routes/` (challenges, points, dogpile, admin)\n52\t- **What**: The archived reference spec (`docs/archive/references/challenge-engine-spec.md`) calls for `challenge-engine` as a standalone internal service with separate verification-workers and reward-service components. M1 implementation lives in the backend monolith for simplicity.\n53\t- **Current mitigation**: Event-driven architecture already decouples all components — handlers communicate via the event queue, not direct function calls. Extraction is mechanical when scale demands it.\n54\t- **Proper solution**: Move challenge engine handlers, routes, and DB helpers to a new `services/challenge-engine/` package. Share the event queue and DB connection. Separate deploy cycle.\n55\t- **Why not now**: At M1 scale, a second service adds deployment complexity for zero benefit. The event queue boundary makes future extraction straightforward.\n56\t\n57\t---\n58\t\n59\t## Post-V1 Backlog (Revisit When More Advanced)\n60\t\n61\tItems that work today but deserve a proper implementation once the platform matures.\n62\t\n63\t### [On-Chain] Stale account cleanup after program redeploys\n64\t- **Date**: 2026-03-15\n65\t- **Location**: `backend/src/worker/settlement.ts`, on-chain accounts\n66\t- **What**: Program redeploys can leave old accounts with incompatible layouts (different enum encoding, removed/reordered fields). Currently the settlement worker caches undecodeable PDAs and skips them after one warning. There's also one permanently undecodeable 888-byte Lord account on devnet from a pre-IDL-change deploy.\n67\t- **Current mitigation**: `undecodeablePdas` set in settlement worker, try/catch per-account in poll loop.\n68\t- **Proper solution**: (1) Admin \"close any PDA\" instruction that skips deserialization (transfer lamports + zero data), (2) Pre-deploy cleanup script that closes all game accounts before upgrade, (3) Account versioning (`version: u8` as first field) so decoders can branch on layout version.\n69\t- **Why not now**: Dev phase — redeploys are frequent, accounts are low-value, and the workaround is adequate.\n70\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"736bbedb-6401-4318-a325-ee85001d8ebf","uuid":"9edd1c4d-fdb3-447c-a931-d575d53e1537","timestamp":"2026-04-22T11:20:43.344Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/TECH_DEBT.md","content":"# Technical Debt & Temporary Fixes\n\nTrack temporary hacks, relaxed rules, and shortcuts here. \n**Goal**: Eliminate these items before V1 Launch (or explicitly defer them).\n\n---\n\n## High Priority (Fix ASAP)\n\n(none)\n\n---\n\n## Medium Priority (Before Launch)\n\n### [Backend] `rateLimitGlobal` is route-local, not app-global\n- **Date**: 2026-04-21\n- **Location**: `backend/src/middleware/rate-limit.ts`, `backend/src/index.ts`, `backend/src/index-waitlist.ts`\n- **What**: `createRateLimitMiddleware(...)` allocates fresh in-memory state per middleware instance, so `rateLimitGlobal` only applies within each mounted route group (`/auth/*`, `/flip-you/*`, `/pot-shot/*`, `/closecall/bet`, waitlist routes) instead of enforcing one shared global bucket across the app.\n- **Current mitigation**: Cloudflare now provides a coarse host-level backstop in front of the API, and route-local in-app limits still protect individual endpoints.\n- **Proper solution**: Either (1) implement a truly shared in-process/global limiter bucket for all route groups that are meant to share `rateLimitGlobal`, or (2) rename/configure the setting to make the route-local scope explicit and document it accordingly.\n- **Why not now**: Current edge rate limiting reduces immediate flood risk, and changing limiter state sharing touches request-shaping behavior that should be validated separately.\n\n### [Backend] Public referral code check endpoint — remove at prod\n- **Date**: 2026-04-15\n- **Location**: `backend/src/routes/public-referral.ts` — `GET /public-referral/code/:code`\n- **What**: Unauthenticated endpoint that checks whether a referral code exists. Added for the waitlist pre-connect flow. Leaks code-existence info without auth — acceptable for waitlist but unnecessary attack surface once the main app launches.\n- **Current mitigation**: Returns only `{ exists: boolean }` (no user info). Regex-validates input.\n- **Proper solution**: Remove endpoint once waitlist is retired and the main app handles referral flows behind auth.\n\n### ~~[Telegram] Webhook errors are too opaque and retry-prone~~\n- **Resolved**: 2026-04-09 — `telegram/src/app.ts` now catches outbound reply delivery failures, logs webhook context, and still returns `200` to Telegram; `telegram/src/telegram-api.ts` now includes Telegram error bodies in thrown errors for faster diagnosis.\n\n### [Challenge Engine] SOL crate payout handler needs production review\n- **Date**: 2026-04-03\n- **Location**: `backend/src/queue/handlers/crate-sol-payout.ts`\n- **What**: `CRATE_SOL_PAYOUT` handler sends SOL from server keypair to player wallet. Needs manual review before production enablement — verify transfer amounts, error handling, retry behavior, and rate limiting against real treasury wallet.\n- **Current mitigation**: Handler marks failed transfers as terminal (no retry). Integration-tested with mock connection only.\n- **Proper solution**: (1) Add retry logic with max attempts (like referral-claim handler), (2) Add rate limiting per user, (3) Verify payout amounts against pool balance, (4) Test with real devnet treasury wallet, (5) Add monitoring/alerting for failed payouts.\n- **Why not now**: M1 launch — handler structure is correct, needs ops hardening before real SOL flows through it.\n\n### ~~[Pot Shot] Backend game-engine PDA helper uses stale `roundNumber` seed~~\n- **Resolved**: 2026-04-02 — `getRoundPda(matchId: Buffer)` already uses correct seed. Confirmed in gap analysis for spec 101.\n\n---\n\n## Low Priority (Post-Launch cleanup)\n\n### [Challenge Engine] Extract to separate service\n- **Date**: 2026-04-04\n- **Location**: `backend/src/queue/handlers/` (game-settled, reward-pool-fund, points-grant, crate-drop, crate-sol-payout), `routes/` (challenges, points, dogpile, admin)\n- **What**: The archived reference spec (`docs/archive/references/challenge-engine-spec.md`) calls for `challenge-engine` as a standalone internal service with separate verification-workers and reward-service components. M1 implementation lives in the backend monolith for simplicity.\n- **Current mitigation**: Event-driven architecture already decouples all components — handlers communicate via the event queue, not direct function calls. Extraction is mechanical when scale demands it.\n- **Proper solution**: Move challenge engine handlers, routes, and DB helpers to a new `services/challenge-engine/` package. Share the event queue and DB connection. Separate deploy cycle.\n- **Why not now**: At M1 scale, a second service adds deployment complexity for zero benefit. The event queue boundary makes future extraction straightforward.\n\n---\n\n## Post-V1 Backlog (Revisit When More Advanced)\n\nItems that work today but deserve a proper implementation once the platform matures.\n\n### [On-Chain] Stale account cleanup after program redeploys\n- **Date**: 2026-03-15\n- **Location**: `backend/src/worker/settlement.ts`, on-chain accounts\n- **What**: Program redeploys can leave old accounts with incompatible layouts (different enum encoding, removed/reordered fields). Currently the settlement worker caches undecodeable PDAs and skips them after one warning. There's also one permanently undecodeable 888-byte Lord account on devnet from a pre-IDL-change deploy.\n- **Current mitigation**: `undecodeablePdas` set in settlement worker, try/catch per-account in poll loop.\n- **Proper solution**: (1) Admin \"close any PDA\" instruction that skips deserialization (transfer lamports + zero data), (2) Pre-deploy cleanup script that closes all game accounts before upgrade, (3) Account versioning (`version: u8` as first field) so decoders can branch on layout version.\n- **Why not now**: Dev phase — redeploys are frequent, accounts are low-value, and the workaround is adequate.\n","numLines":70,"startLine":1,"totalLines":70}}}
